NYC taxi trips tip prediction

Lovdip Singh

Goal of study

To analyse NYC Taxi data and fit a model to predict taxi tips.

Cleaning the data

Tips are only for credit card data, we begin by only considering payments made by credit card.

Renaming pickup and drop off time variables will be helpful for clarity and deriving other variables. This includes the day of week variable, the hour the trip started and the duration of the trip.

An extra_costs variable will also be added by summing existing extra, mta_tax, improvement_surcharge, tolls_amount variables.

# read in file
w2 <- read_csv('../data/taxi/week2.csv')
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   VendorID = col_double(),
##   tpep_pickup_datetime = col_datetime(format = ""),
##   tpep_dropoff_datetime = col_datetime(format = ""),
##   passenger_count = col_double(),
##   trip_distance = col_double(),
##   pickup_longitude = col_double(),
##   pickup_latitude = col_double(),
##   RatecodeID = col_double(),
##   store_and_fwd_flag = col_character(),
##   dropoff_longitude = col_double(),
##   dropoff_latitude = col_double(),
##   payment_type = col_double(),
##   fare_amount = col_double(),
##   extra = col_double(),
##   mta_tax = col_double(),
##   tip_amount = col_double(),
##   tolls_amount = col_double(),
##   improvement_surcharge = col_double(),
##   total_amount = col_double()
## )
nrow(w2)
## [1] 2651287
w2 <- w2 %>% 
  filter(payment_type == 1) %>% # tips are only for credit card payment type
  mutate(dropoff_datetime = tpep_dropoff_datetime,
         pickup_datetime = tpep_pickup_datetime,
         dow = factor(wday(pickup_datetime,label=TRUE,abbr=TRUE, week_start=1), ordered = FALSE), #add day of week
         hour_trip_start = as.numeric(hour(pickup_datetime)), # add hour trip started
         trip_duration = as.numeric(difftime(dropoff_datetime,pickup_datetime,units="mins"))) # trip duration in minutes

# create extra_costs variable
w2 <- w2 %>% select(extra, mta_tax, improvement_surcharge, tolls_amount) %>%
  transmute(extra_costs = rowSums(.)) %>% 
  bind_cols(w2, .)

Filtering by credit card payments only has reduced the number of trips by 877,849.

There are a few concerns on some data. There are unusually large trip_distances, trip_duration, fare_amount, tip_amount, tolls_amount. RatecodeID should only take values 1 to 6, some negative values for dollar variables and distances. Negative values clearly wont be helpful in the model, so these observations will have to be discarded.

We can check the values of the variables with relatively large max values to determine appropriate cutoff values for the variables.

After filtering the trip distance, there are still some extreme duration values. Clear errors in trip duration, there are quite a few (~1700) trips over 1400 minutes, which is an unusually large amount, most likely sensors that are left on for a day as 1400 minutes ~24 hours. Trip duration \(\leq 100\) minutes seems appropriate.

Taking the tip amount with a limit of \(\$20\) seems appropriate, there are large amounts of data available for these numbers which is good. Higher values are likely to hinder the model. This also means that our model can only generalise to tips between \(\$0\) and \(\$20\).

w2$RatecodeID <- as.character(w2$RatecodeID)
w2 <- w2 %>%
  filter(passenger_count %in% c(1:6), # max 6 passengers
         RatecodeID %in% as.character(c(1:6)), # valid values for RatecodeID
         tip_amount <= 20 & tip_amount >= 0)

Everything seems good, after this filtration, 10,000 trips were removed.

We can create some categorical variables from the numeric data as linear relationships may be more likely to be present in these categories rather than numeric data. Lets use the hour_trip_start variable and create time_of_day variable for each 6 hour interval of a day. For example if a trip starts in the hours between midnight and 6am lets call this early morning, etc..

w2$time_of_day <- NA 
w2$time_of_day[w2$hour_trip_start >= 0 & w2$hour_trip_start <= 5] <- 'early morning'
w2$time_of_day[w2$hour_trip_start >= 6 & w2$hour_trip_start <= 11] <- 'morning'
w2$time_of_day[w2$hour_trip_start >= 12 & w2$hour_trip_start <= 17] <- 'evening'
w2$time_of_day[w2$hour_trip_start >= 17 & w2$hour_trip_start <= 23] <- 'night'
w2$time_of_day <- factor(w2$time_of_day, levels=c('early morning', 'morning','evening', 'night'))

w2 %>% group_by(time_of_day) %>% summarise(n()) %>% arrange(time_of_day)

We can also use pick up longitude and latitude values to make sure all pickups are in NYC and also classify each pick up by their respective borough. This can be done by using a shapefile for NYC.

nyc_boro <- read_sf('geo_export_8bbd3dcd-7071-42e8-a21f-8adb61e9e2ee.shp')

(map <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=nyc_boro, aes(fill=boro_name)) +
  labs(title="New York City Boroughs", fill='Borough'))

Lets classify pick up coordinates to their particular NYC borough to filter non NYC pick ups.

coords = w2[,c('pickup_longitude', 'pickup_latitude')]
pnts_sf <- st_as_sf(coords, coords=c('pickup_longitude', 'pickup_latitude'), crs = st_crs(nyc_boro))
boroughs <- pnts_sf %>% mutate(
  intersection=as.integer(st_intersects(geometry, nyc_boro)),
  borough = ifelse(is.na(intersection), NA, nyc_boro$boro_name[intersection])
)
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
w2 <- w2 %>% 
  mutate(pickup_borough = boroughs$borough)

w2 %>% group_by(pickup_borough) %>%

Model building

Cross validation code:

allyhat <- function(xtrain, ytrain, xtest, lambdas, nvmax=50){
  n <- nrow(xtrain)
  yhat <- matrix(nrow=nrow(xtest), ncol=length(lambdas))
  search <- regsubsets(xtrain, ytrain, nvmax=nvmax, method="back")
  summ <- summary(search)
  for(i in 1:length(lambdas)){
    penMSE <- n * log(summ$rss) + lambdas[i] * (1:(nvmax))
    best <- which.min(penMSE)  #lowest AIC
    betahat <- coef(search, best) #coefficients
    xinmodel <- cbind(1,xtest)[,summ$which[best,]] #predictors in that model
    yhat[,i] <- xinmodel %*% betahat
  }
  yhat
}

There will be 8 variables included in the linear model for prediction of tips.

To get an unbiased estimate of the mean squared prediction error for week 2 data we can use 10 fold cross validation. The strategy is to do backwards step wise search to find the model with the smallest penalised RSS, for a given \(\lambda\) parameter. \(\text{Penalised (RSS)}(\lambda) = nlog\text{RSS}+\lambda p\). Regsubsets will find the best models with 1 to 50 parameters, we can the use the RSS of these models to find the model with the lowest penalised RSS for each value of \(\lambda\). The predicted values of the model are recorded for each of the test sets. This results is an unbiased estimate of mean squared prediction error for each of the values of \(\lambda\).

set.seed(6288842)

# variables to be included in model
subset <- w2[, c('extra_costs',
                 'standard_rate',
                 'fare_amount',
                 'dow',
                 'queens',
                 'trip_duration',
                 'trip_distance',
                 'time_of_day',
                 'tip_amount')]



mf <- model.frame(tip_amount~.^2, data=subset)
X <- model.matrix(tip_amount~.^2, mf)[,-1]
y <- subset$tip_amount
n <- nrow(X)

set.seed(6288842)
folds <- sample(rep(1:10, length.out=n))

lambdas <- c(2,4,6,8,10,12)
fitted <- matrix(nrow=n, ncol=length(lambdas))

for(k in 1:10){
  train <- (1:n)[folds!=k]
  test <- (1:n)[folds==k]
  fitted[test,] <- allyhat(X[train,], y[train], X[test,], lambdas)  
}

colMeans((y - fitted)^2)
## [1] 1.395328 1.395328 1.395328 1.395328 1.395328 1.395338

Cross validation shows that \(\lambda=2\) is fine to use, there is little difference in MSPE between models using the different values of \(\lambda\).

search = regsubsets(X, y, nvmax = 50, method = "backward")
summ = summary(search)
aic = n * log(summ$rss) + 2 * (1:50)
best = which.min(aic)
betahat = coef(search, best)

Applying the model

The MSPE for the null model, i.e. variance of the tips in the filtered data is ~6 and has a mean of ~2.8. Reducing this MSPE to ~1.7 is respectable, the model explains 70% of the variation in the filtered data. This model considers tips up to $20.
